nextcloud-mcp-server for Debian
================================

Known gap: unpackaged hard runtime dependencies
-------------------------------------------------

pyproject.toml lists the following as hard (non-optional) runtime
dependencies. None of them currently has a Debian package available in
the apt repo, so they are deliberately NOT listed in debian/control's
Depends field. This package therefore builds and installs, but is not
yet a fully functional runtime until these are packaged in follow-up
sessions:

  - fastembed             (pulls in onnxruntime/tokenizers; substantial)
  - anthropic             (needs `jiter`, a Rust/PyO3 extension)
  - langchain-text-splitters (needs langchain-core, a large package)
  - pymupdf4llm
  - pypdfium2
  - qdrant-client

qdrant-client has debian/ packaging (source qdrant-client, Jenkins job
Foregin/qdrant-client) and builds a local .deb cleanly, but is not yet
published to the apt repo — see "CI publish-step gap" below. Add it back
to Depends once python3-qdrant-client is installable via apt.

fastembed is blocked on a substantial Rust crate-packaging effort — see
"fastembed / tokenizers Rust crate gap" below.

CI Test-stage gap: Jenkins build agent likely has a stale cached vitexsoftware/<dist> image
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

As of 2026-07-11, every sibling OpenTelemetry/mistralai/qdrant-client
Jenkins job (Foregin/python-opentelemetry-*, Foregin/mistralai,
Foregin/qdrant-client) fails with a bare "ERROR: script returned exit
code 100", but the per-distro dpkg-buildpackage build and artifact
archiving steps succeed first (confirmed via archived .deb artifacts and
clean build logs with no ValueError/dpkg-buildpackage: error) — the
packaging itself is correct.

Root cause, confirmed by reading the actual Jenkins Test-stage log
(Foregin/python-opentelemetry-semantic-conventions build #3): the
shared Jenkinsfile's "Test <dist>" stage does
`sudo apt-get -y install python3-<pkg>` inside a
vitexsoftware/<dist> container against the live apt sources (Debian
archive + repo.vitexsoftware.com). That install fails with:

  python3-opentelemetry-semantic-conventions : Depends: python3-typing-extensions (>= 4.5.0) but it is not going to be installed
                                               Depends: python3-opentelemetry-api (>= 1.41.1) but it is not installable
  E: Unable to correct problems, you have held broken packages.

At first this looked like it was caused by repo.vitexsoftware.com's
backports component 403ing/404ing on every distribution (visible in the
same logs as "E: Failed to fetch .../backports/binary-amd64/Packages
... 403 Forbidden" / "404 Not Found" across bookworm/trixie/jammy/
noble/resolute). That symptom is now GONE (verified 2026-07-11: all
five distros' backports indexes return HTTP 200, and build #4's log
shows every distro fetching backports cleanly) — but the exact same
"python3-opentelemetry-api ... not installable" failure still occurs.

This was reproduced and disproven as a repo problem: a clean
`debian:trixie` container (not the custom vitexsoftware/trixie Jenkins
image), configured with the same repo.vitexsoftware.com apt source and
signing key, installs `python3-opentelemetry-api` +
`python3-typing-extensions` together with a completely clean dependency
resolution (no held/broken packages). So the live apt repository itself
is healthy right now.

That points at the Jenkins build agent's own environment: the
Jenkinsfile does `buildImage = docker.image(vendor + '/' + distro)`
then `buildImage.inside { ... }` without ever calling `.pull()` on it,
so the Jenkins host almost certainly runs off a **locally cached,
possibly stale** `vitexsoftware/<dist>` image (baked apt package lists
or `/etc/apt/preferences` pins from whenever it was last pulled) rather
than re-resolving against the live repo state. Fix candidates for
whoever has Jenkins-host access: `docker pull vitexsoftware/{bookworm,
trixie,jammy,noble,resolute}` on the build agent, or add `.pull()` (or
an `--pull always` build-arg equivalent) to the Jenkinsfile's
`docker.image(...)` calls so each build always starts from a fresh
image. This needs Jenkins-host access not available in this
environment; a Debian package built locally with
`dpkg-buildpackage -us -uc -b` is correct even though its Jenkins CI
Test stage cannot currently verify installability end-to-end.

Build fix: unrecognized trove classifiers
-------------------------------------------

Debian's packaged python3-hatchling (1.27.0) validates PyPI classifiers
against an older trove-classifiers list that does not recognize
"Framework :: OpenTelemetry" or "Programming Language :: Python :: 3.13"
/ "3.14", and raises a hard ValueError during the build backend's
metadata step. Every opentelemetry-python(-contrib) sibling package's
debian/rules now strips these classifiers from pyproject.toml in
override_dh_auto_configure before invoking dh_auto_configure. This one
resolved the Jenkins bookworm/trixie build failures that had been
silently masking as "completed" packaging tasks (verified only by local
dpkg-buildpackage, which uses a newer, more permissive hatchling).

These are left in place in upstream's own pyproject.toml dependency list
(removing them there would misrepresent what the software actually
needs); the gap is purely at the Debian packaging level.

fastembed / tokenizers Rust crate gap
--------------------------------------

fastembed depends on `tokenizers` (HuggingFace's Rust/PyO3 tokenizer
library) and, transitively via `qdrant-client[fastembed]`-style usage,
`py-rust-stemmers`. A crate-graph audit (2026-07-09) found ~40-45
librust-*-dev packages are needed before these can build from source in
Debian, including:

  - Two INCOMPATIBLE pyo3 lines: py-rust-stemmers needs pyo3 ^0.28.3,
    tokenizers pins pyo3 0.26.0. Debian's archive only has 0.22.6.
    Both need packaging as new parallel-version librust-pyo3-0.2X-dev
    packages (Debian's multi-version crate convention), not in-place
    bumps to the existing 0.22 line.
  - Missing leaf crates: serde_core, rust-stemmers, esaxx-rs,
    spm_precompiled, unicode-normalization-alignments, ndarray, numpy
    (rust crate), monostate/monostate-impl, jiff-static,
    macro_rules_attribute(-proc-macro), once_cell_polyfill,
    pyo3-async-runtimes, rayon-cond, unit-prefix, find-msvc-tools.
  - Version-incompatible crates needing parallel-version packages
    (archive-wide in-place bumps are risky — wide reverse-dependency
    surface): rustix (0.38 -> 1.x major), rustc-hash (1.x -> 2.x major),
    rand/rand_core/rand_chacha (0.8 -> 0.9), zerocopy/zerocopy-derive
    (0.7 -> 0.8), getrandom (0.2 -> 0.3), once_cell, heck,
    target-lexicon, itertools, jiff, memoffset, onig_sys, base64,
    dary_heap.

This is being worked bottom-up (leaves first) as a dedicated
sub-effort; see task tracker for current progress. `debcargo` does not
recurse — each missing/incompatible crate must be packaged manually,
in dependency order, before its dependents will build.

Build backend note
-------------------

Upstream builds with `uv_build` (see pyproject.toml [build-system]),
which is not packaged for Debian. debian/rules patches pyproject.toml at
build time (override_dh_auto_configure) to use hatchling instead, and
restores the original pyproject.toml afterwards (override_dh_auto_clean).

